Lung cancer has a high degree of molecular heterogeneity thus giving rise to diverse pathological features. Cases are classified according to respective histological characteristics leading to the distinction between small and non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC) (
 Herbst et al., 2008). The onslaught of molecular targets has driven a shift in therapeutic management from conventional cytotoxic drugs to targeted molecular targeted therapy (
 Hirsch et al., 2017; 
 Herbst et al., 2018). The pathogenesis of lung cancer and its management has been covered extensively by others in the preceding reviews. CD151 was the first tetraspanin to be identified as a tumor promoter (
 Testa et al., 1999). The authors found that the monoclonal antibody raised against CD151 was capable of inhibiting both spontaneous and experimental metastasis in the chick embryo chorioallantoic membrane model. Since then, CD151 overexpression has been implicated as a negative prognostic indicator in numerous solid malignancies (
 Ang et al., 2004; 
 Chien et al., 2008; 
 Ke et al., 2009; 
 Suzuki et al., 2011; 
 Kwon et al., 2012; 
 Lee et al., 2012; 
 Kang et al., 2013; 
 Romanska et al., 2013; 
 Fisher et al., 2016; 
 Medrano et al., 2017).
